Tables{\*\bkmkend D2HTopicM47}
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 The Tables list on the left side of the Data Builder shows the file names of the tables in an application's data dictionary.  The table names that begin wit
h S<Prefix> are the system tables that ProMatrix adds to an application.  
\par When a table name is highlighted, a brief description of the table appears directly below the Tables list, and the Fields list on the right side of the Data Builder displays the fields in the table.
\par The push buttons to the right of the Tables list allow you to create, modify and manage an application's  tables.   
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber3}\'b7\tab }The New and Add buttons let you create new tables or add existing tables to the data dictionary.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }T{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber3}he Index, Propertie
s, Structure, Remove, Rename, Update, Utilities and Browse buttons help you modify and manage the tables in the data dictionary.  These buttons operate on the table highlighted on the Tables list.
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb180\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Table Names}
  Consider using the ProMatrix file naming conventions for the tables you create for an application.  If you adopt the ProMatrix file naming rules, your tables will be easily distinguishable from ProMatrix system tables, your tables will have application-
specific names and your table names will help identify a table's function in your applications. 
