\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 The Data Builder stores a great deal of information about a table and its fields.  You may decide not to enter all the information the Data Builder stores for every table and every fiel
d.  Certainly, you don't have to set up all field properties before you start using a table to build application objects.  Most field properties can be entered and changed at any time.
\par \pard \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1\keepn 
However, there certain table and field properties that should be entered before you start building application objects.  If you don't enter these table and field properties, ProMatrix won't be able to provide all its automatic features that help you build
 application objects.  
\par The following is an overview of the minimum steps required to enter a table in an application's data dictionary.  It points out the table and field properties that should be set up before you build an application object that uses a table.  
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To enter a table in an application's data dictionary and set up required table and field properties
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber4}1.\tab 
Click the New button to create a new table or click the Add button to find existing tables.  ProMatrix displays appropriate dialogs to either create or add a table.
\par 2.\tab If you're creating a new table, enter its fields, field types and field dimensions.  If you're adding existing tables, you can add more than one table at a time.  You can even add all the tables in a directory at once.
\par 3.\tab {\b Required Indexes:}  For the table you've created or added, click the Index button.  ProMatrix displays the Index dialog that allows you to create and modify a table's indexes.{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 \tab You may create other indexes for the table at this time.
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 4.\tab {\b T{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber4}able Properties:  }Click the table Properties button.  ProMatrix displays the table Properties dialog.
  Enter a Description for the table.  Click the Primary Key popup and select the primary key index tag.
\par \pard\plain \s75\li360\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\cs71\b Primary Key}
  The primary key is the field or combination of fields that uniquely identifies each record in a table.  It is important that you identify each table's primary key because ProMatrix uses the primary key to automatically set up certain data integrity rule
s.  ProMatrix automatically prevents the entry of duplicate primary keys in screens built through the Object Builder. 
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\b 5.\tab Referential Integrity:}
  If the table contains a foreign key matching the primary key of another table, select the foreign key field(s) in the Field List and click the Integrity field property check box to set up Referential Integrity validation for the field(s) in the foreign 
key.  ProMatrix uses your Referential Integrity validation setup to determine how tables are related to each other in an application.
\par \pard\plain \s75\li360\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Parent-Child Relations}  You may be more familiar with Parent-Child terminology than referential integrity terms.  A table
 with a foreign key matching the primary key of another table is called a "child table" by some developers.  The table with the matching primary key is called a "parent" table.  In these terms, when you use the Data Builder's Integrity field property to s
et up Referential Integrity validation, you are actually defining a relationship between a child and parent table.
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 6.\tab {\b Field Labels:}  For each table field that will appear on a screen or report, select the field in the Field list.  Click the Label field prop
erty check box to enter a descriptive label for the field.  The label you enter will be automatically displayed when you create screens or reports that use the field.
\par 7.\tab {\b Field Pictures:}
 For each table field that will appear on a screen or report, select the field in the Field list.  Click the Picture field property check box to enter a picture expression that defines the field display.  The picture expression you enter will be automatic
ally used to display the field on screens and reports.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 You can, of cours
e, set up all table and field properties before you start creating application objects.  In fact, you are encouraged to do so.  It's probably more productive and efficient to use the Data Builder to set up all table and field properties at one time than t
o do it piecemeal.
\par The remainder of this chapter provides the details on using the Data Builder to build your application's data.
