\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 For each table you create or add to a project, you must create the following indexes:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber10}\'b7\tab }{\b Primary Key Index:}
  Create an index for the table's primary key.  You may want to call the tag  "PrimaryKey".  If you've added a table, a primary key index may already exist.  
\par \tab {\b Important:  }If the primary key consists of more than one field, create another index for just the first field in the primary key.  This index optimizes the speed at which ProMatrix checks for duplicate primary keys when a user adds or ed
its a record on a screen.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b Child Table Indexes:}
\par \tab 
If a table is a child table that will be displayed on a screen in a related screens group, create an index for the foreign key that links child records to the primary key in the child's parent table.  If the foreign key consists of more than one field, a
lso create a separate index for the first field in the foreign key.
\par \tab The indexes you create for related screens child tables must begin with the foreign key field(s) in the child table that links to the prima
ry key field(s) in the parent table.  Any subsequent fields you include in a child table index will determine the order in which the child table records are displayed on the child screen when the index is selected via the Order push button control.
\par \tab 
For example, let's say your parent table is a customer table with a customer number field (Cust_No) as its primary key.  Further, let's say the child table is an invoice table that also contains the customer number field (Cust_No) as the foreign key fiel
d linkin
g invoice records to customer records.  Then, every index you create for the invoice table must have the Cust_No field as the first field in the index.  The remaining fields you include in an invoice table index will determine the order in which the invoi
ce records are displayed on the invoice screen when the index is selected via the Order push button control.  Also, to optimize the speed of accessing invoice records, you should create an index for the invoice table on the Cust_No field alone.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b D{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber10}ELETED() Function Index:}
  By default ProMatrix recycles deleted records.  That means that when a user adds a record to a table on a screen, ProMatrix attempts to find a deleted record to reuse for the new record.  Recycling deleted records helps keep the number of deleted record
s in a table to a minimum and avoids the need to frequently PACK a table.  
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 For large tables with many thousands of records, it can take some time for ProMatrix to find a deleted record after a user clicks the Add push button.  However, if yo
u create an index for a table based on the DELETED() function, you will optimize the speed at which ProMatrix finds deleted records.
\par ProMatrix automatically creates a DELETED() index tag when you create a new table in the Data Builder.  It is suggested that you also create an index based on the DELETED() function for tables you add to a project.\tab 
