\par \pard\plain \s4\sb216\sa14\keepn \b\f5 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} CalculatedDefaultValues.33}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $}
 Calculated Default Values}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Calculated Default Values}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0125}}{\f103 
 }Calculated Default Values
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
Sometimes a field's default value must be calculated using some formula or calculation expression.  The calculation might involve other fields in the same or other tables, or the calculation might involve fixed parameters.  {\b 
In this case, you don't enter a default value in the Default Value dialog, you enter screen code to calculate and display the default value.
\par }\pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To set up a calculated default value for a field
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber27}1.\tab 
Open the screen set Object Editor to edit the screen that contains the field using the FoxPro Screen Builder.  Select the Layout option on the Screen menu.  On the Screen Layout dialog, click the Code button in the Options box.  On the Screen Code dial
og, click the On Refresh (Show Gets) button.
\par 2.\tab E{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber27}nter code in the following format in the On Refresh (Show Gets) Code Snippet dialog:
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 {\b\f11 IF sglAdding AND sglEditing
\par   REPLACE <field name> WITH <calculation expression>
\par }\pard \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 {\b\f11 ENDIF
\par }
The memory variables sglAdding and sglEditing are ProMatrix provided memory variables that are set to true when the Add control is selected.  The <calculation expression> provides the calculated value.  You may need to enter code before the REPLACE statem
ent that calculates the value.  ProMatrix issues a SHOW GETS to run this code.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 In some cases, you might want to create a table's primary key by sequentially incrementing a numeric value as records are add
ed to the table.  You can use the calculated default value approach to calculate new primary keys.
\par For example, a customer table might contain a Customer Number field as its primary key.  For each customer record added, the Customer Number field can contain a default value equal to the highest Customer Number already used incremented by one.  The follo
wing On Refresh (Show Gets) code would calculate the default customer number:
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 {\b\f11 IF sglAdding AND sglEditing
\par     slnRecNo = RECNO( )
\par     slnHighest = 0
\par     SCAN
\par    \tab  IF cust_no > slnHighest
\par            slnHighest = cust_no
\par        ENDIF
\par     ENDSCAN
\par     GOTO slnRecNo
\par     REPLACE cust_no WITH slnHighest+1
\par }\pard \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 {\b\f11 ENDIF
\par }\pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 The preceding example will work well for small tables in a single-user environment, but it won't handle large tables and multi-user environments very well.
\par  A more robust code example for calculating primary keys is shown below.  This code example is an improvement over the preceding example in two ways:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sa60\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber28}\'b7\tab }{\b Speed:}  This new code example calculates a primary key much faster for large tables.
\par \pard \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b M{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber28}ulti-user:  }
In a multi-user environment each added record will have a unique primary key .  The last calculated primary key is stored in the Default field of the primary key field's data dictionary record.  When a record is added, the Default field value is increment
ed by 1 and placed into the primary key field.  
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 The code shown below would be placed in a Customer screen's On Refresh (Show Gets) snippet to calculate unique Customer numbers for a Customer table's primary key. 
 You will find a file named SSYSUPKC.PRG in the ProMatrix \\PRGS that contains the code shown below.  
\par \pard\plain \s78 \b\f11\fs18 {\fs16 IF sglAdding AND sglEditing
\par     slnHighest = 0
\par     slnCurWork = SELECT( )
\par     * Open/select the application's DD2 table.
\par     slcDD2 = sgcPDD2 && Name of application's DD2 table (includes path)
\par     slcDD2Alias = slcDD2
\par     slnDot = AT('.',slcDD2Alias)
\par     IF slnDot > 0
\par         slcDD2Alias = LEFT(slcDD2Alias,slnDot-1)
\par     ENDIF
\par     slcDD2Alias = SUBSTR(slcDD2Alias,RAT('\\',slcDD2Alias)+1)
\par     sllDD2Open = .T.
\par     IF USED(slcDD2Alias)
\par         SELECT (slcDD2Alias)
\par     ELSE
\par         IF NOT &sgcUUse(slcDD2)
\par             sllDD2Open = .F.
\par         ENDIF
\par     ENDIF
\par     IF sllDD2Open
\par         * Find the DD2 record of the customer number field.
\par         SET ORDER TO TAG file_name
\par         SEEK 'CUSTOMER.DBFCUST_NO   '
\par         IF FOUND( )
\par         * Lock the DD2 record until the new customer number is recorded
\par         * so that another user cannot use the same new customer number.
\par             IF &sgcURL( )\tab \tab \tab 
\par                 REPLACE default WITH ALLTRIM(STR(VAL(default)+1))
\par                 slnHighest = VAL(default)
\par                 UNLOCK
\par             ENDIF
\par         ENDIF
\par     ENDIF
\par     SELECT (slnCurWork)
\par     IF slnHighest > 0
\par         REPLACE cust_no WITH slnHighest
\par     ELSE
\par        * Attempt to determine customer number has failed so cancel add.
\par         ?? CHR(7)
\par         WAIT WINDOW NOWAIT ;
\par             'Unable to determine customer number, add cancelled.'
\par       * Setting sglEditing to false will cancel the add.  See the siAdd 
\par       * function in S<prefix>Ctrl.prg.
\par         sglEditing = .F.
\par         RETURN
\par     ENDIF
\par ENDIF
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb340\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} Label.34}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Label}}{
\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Label}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0130}}{\f103\fs24  }Label
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Click the Label check box to enter a label for a field.  ProMatrix displays the Label dialog.  Enter the field's label in the Label field on the dialog.
\par ProMatrix displays field labels on the Data Builder Field list.
\par When you create a screen or report for a table, ProMatrix automatically inserts the field labels.  Therefore, you should enter labels for table fields before you use the table to create screens and reports. 
