\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
You don't normally use the Permissions field property while developing an application.  If your application is multiuser, the system administrator who manages an installation of your application uses the Permissions property on the Data Manager to set sec
urity permissions for a field.
\par When a user clicks the Permissions check box, ProMatrix displays the Field Permissions dialog.  This dialog shows a list of Field Permission groups.  The system
 administrator creates Field Permission Groups on the Field Permission Groups dialog reached from the Admin menu Security popup.  The system administrator assigns application users to Field Permission Groups on the Users screen also reached from the Secur
ity popup.
\par For each Field Permission Group listed on the dialog, the system administrator selects the field restriction from the radio buttons in the Restriction box.  The restriction determines a user's right to view and edit a field on the screens in your
 application.  The field restriction alternatives have the following meanings:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber29}\'b7\tab }{\b None }- members of the Field Permission Group have full rights to view and edit the field.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b Display Only} - members of the Field Permission Group can view the field but cannot edit it.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b N{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber29}o Display} - members of the Field Permission Group cannot see the field.
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb340\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} Message.37}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Message}}{
\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Message}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0145}}{\f103\fs24  }Message
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Click the Message check box to set up a message to display when a field is edited.  ProMatrix brings up the Message Expression dialog.  Enter an expression
 that defines your message.  Normally, you enter either:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber30}\'b7\tab }A text message enclosed in quotation marks, or
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }A{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber30} call to a user-defined function that returns the message.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
If you're using a program to display the message, you can click the Find Program button to find the name of the program file that displays your message. ProMatrix enters the name of the program followed by "()"on the Message Expression dialog.  Complete t
he entry of the message expression with the program name.
\par When a field is edited on a scr
een you create with ProMatrix, the message is displayed at the bottom of your application's main window.  If you've included the status bar in your application, the message appears on the status bar.  You can include the status bar in an application by ch
ecking the Status Bar check box on the Environment dialog reached from the ProMatrix Options menu.
