\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Comments}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0150}}{\f103\fs24  }Comments
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Click the Comments check box to enter field comments.  ProMatrix displays the Comments dialog.  Enter any comments you want to record about a field in the Comments dialog.
\par The comments dialog can be used to provide users of your application important information about a field.
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb340\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} Help.39}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Help}}{\f103\fs24  
}{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Help}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0155}}{\f103\fs24  }Help
\par \pard\plain \s66\sa120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
Click the Help check box to enter field-level help text.  ProMatrix brings up the Help dialog.  Enter your help text in the text box.  You do not need to enclose the text you enter in quotation marks on the Help dialog.
\par When a user edits a field and presses F3, the help text you enter is displayed in a field help window.  The window title bar contains the field label.  If you haven't entered a label for a field, the title bar contains the field name.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
Since the help text is available when a user edits a field, your help text should aid the user in entering data into the field.  An explanation of the field's purpose plus any rules governing the data the user can enter would be appropriate.
\par If you include the ProMatrix Data Manager in an application, users of the application can access the Help field property to enter useful notations about a field to aid them in data entry.  
\par \pard\plain \s7\sb216\sa60 \b\f5\fs28 F3 Edit Permission
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
If a user has the permission to edit F3 field-level help on screen, the user can press Alt-F3 to display the field help window in edit mode.  The user can then enter and modify the help text for a field while editing the field on screen.  See the {\i 
Security} chapter to learn how to give a user the permission to edit F3 help on screen.
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb340\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} Error.40}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Error}}{
\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Error}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0160}}{\f103\fs24  }Error
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Click the Error check box to set up a message to display when a field is edited and the data entered fails validation.  ProMatrix
 brings up the Error Expression dialog. Enter an expression that defines your error message.  Normally, you enter either:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber31}\'b7\tab }A text error message enclosed in quotation marks, or
\par \pard \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sa240\sl281\slmult1\tx360 {\f1 \'b7\tab }A{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber31} call to a user-defined function that returns the error message.
\par \pard\plain \s67\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
If you're using a program to display the message, you can click the Find Program button to find the name of the program file that displays your message. ProMatrix enters the name of the program followed by "()"on the Message Expression dialog.  Complete t
he entry of the message expression with the program name.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
The ProMatrix validation routine displays your error message in the system message window in the upper-right corner of an application's main window.  The ProMatrix validation routine displays the message if the data entered into the field fails the valida
tion rules set up for the field through the field's Integrity property.  If you don't enter your own error message, ProMatrix displays "Invalid Input" when a field fails validation. 
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb340\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} When.41}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} When}}{\f103\fs24  
}{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} When}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0165}}{\f103\fs24  }When
\par \pard\plain \s66\sa120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Click the When check box to enter a logical expression that must be true before a field can be edited.  ProMatrix brings up the When Expression dialog.  Enter your logical expression in the text box.
\par \pard\plain \s67\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 When a user enters the edit mode on a screen, the cursor will not go on a field whose When expression evaluates to false.  
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb362\sa43\keepn \b\f5\fs36 {\f103 {\*\bkmkstart D2HTopicM4}\page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} DataIntegrity.42}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 
\b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Data Integrity}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Data Integrity}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +}
 SECTION1:0170}}{\f103\fs24  }Data Integrity{\*\bkmkend D2HTopicM4}
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 You should rarely, if ever, have to write any code to validate fields on your data entry screens.  The Integrity check box on the Data Builder brings up the ProMatrix Integrity d
ialog.  The Integrity dialog makes it easy for you to enter sophisticated validation rules for any field.  
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb180\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Users can do it!}
  If you include the ProMatrix Data Manager in your application, the users can set up field validation for themselves.  Often only users know how a field should be validated.  ProMatrix makes user validation set up possible and easy.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 ProMatrix enforces full data integrity.  Data integrity means data must be valid.  Enforcing data integrity means that ProMatrix makes sure that an applic
ation's data complies with the set of validation rules you enter through the Data Builder.
\par Data integrity involves entity, domain and referential integrity.  Briefly, here's how ProMatrix handles data integrity:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber32}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b E{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber32}ntity Integrity}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
Entity integrity means that primary keys cannot be null or duplicated.  When you identify a table's primary key on the Data Builder's Properties dialog, ProMatrix automatically sets up validation rules for the primary key fields to prevent null or duplica
te values from being entered when adding or editing data on application screens. 
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber33}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b D{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber33}omain Integrity}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
Domain integrity means that every field value must be a member of a predefined domain.  You define a field's domain through the Integrity check box on the Data Builder.  You can define a field's domain as a range of values, a set of values, a table of val
ues or as simply not null.  You can also enter program code to define a domain.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\keepn\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber34}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b R{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber34}eferential Integrity}
\par \pard\plain \s46\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart PlaceHolder1}{\*\bkmkend PlaceHolder1}Referential Integrity means that if a table includes a foreign key matching a 
primary key of another table, every value of the foreign key must be equal to the value of a primary key in the other table.  Referential integrity must also take into account what happens to foreign keys when a primary key value is changed or deleted.

\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
In ProMatrix you set up referential integrity for foreign key fields through the Integrity check box on the Data Builder.  The Integrity dialog lets you identify the table that contains the matching primary key.  It also lets you map the foreign key field
s to their corresponding primary key fields.  For both primary key changes and deletions, you can choose one of the following four referential integrity rules to apply to the foreign key: (1) restrict, (2) set null, (3) cascade or (4) no change.
\par When users add or edit foreign key fields on application screens, ProMatrix prevents foreign key values that don't match a related primary key.  When users change or delete a primary key, ProMatrix applies the referential integrity rule you have selected 
for tables with matching foreign keys.
