\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 When you choose Range validation for a field, the valid entries in the field must fall in the range you enter on the Integrity dialog.  
\par Range validation is useful for numeric fields that have minimum and maximum values.  In a financial application (for example, payroll), range validation can prevent the entry of , say, an erroneous salary rate that is much too small or large. 
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To create a range of valid entries for a field
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber38}1.\tab Select Range validation on the Type popup.  ProMatrix transforms the Integrity dialog for Range validation.
\par 2.\tab Enter the low value in the range in the From field and the high value in the To field.  
\par 3.\tab Click the Options popup to turn on validation for the field.  Choose the validation option that you want for the field.
\par 4.\tab C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber38}lick OK .
\par \pard\plain \s4\sb216\sa14\keepn \b\f5 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} Set.45}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Set}}{\f103  }{
\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Set}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0185}}{\f103  }Set
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
When you choose Set validation for a field, the valid entries in the field must be members of the set of values you enter on the Integrity dialog.  The set of values and a description of each value are shown in a list box on the Integrity dialog.
\par Set validation is useful for character fields that contain codes.  Human Resources databases typically contain fields with codes that identify an employee's status, employment type, benefits coverage and so on.  Set validati
on is ideal for these kinds of fields.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To create a set of valid entries for a field
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber39}1.\tab Select Set validation on the Type popup.  ProMatrix transforms the Integrity dialog for Set validation.
\par 2.\tab Click the Add button.  ProMatrix puts the cursor on the Value field.
\par 3.\tab Enter a set value into the Value field.  Tab to the Desc field.
\par 4.\tab Enter a description of the value in the Desc field.  Press Enter or Tab.  ProMatrix puts the value and description entered in the list box and moves the cursor to the Add button.
\par 5.\tab To add another value to the set, press Enter and repeat steps 3 - 4. 
\par 6.\tab Repeat steps 3 - 5 for each value you want to add to the set.
\par 7.\tab When you're finished entering set values, click the Options popup to turn on validation for the field.  Choose the validation option that you want for the field.
\par 8.\tab C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber39}lick OK.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To change a value in the set of valid entries for a field
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 1.\tab Highlight the set value that you want to change in the list box.
\par 2.\tab Click the Change button.  ProMatrix displays the set value and its description in the Value and Desc fields.
\par 3.\tab Make your changes in the Value and Desc fields.
\par 4.\tab With the cursor in the Desc field, press Enter or Tab to exit the change mode.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To delete a value from the set of valid entries for a field
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 1.\tab Highlight the set value that you want to delete in the list box.
\par 2.\tab Click the Delete button.
\par \pard\plain \s6\sb120 \b\f5 Order
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 You can change the order in which the set values are shown in the list box by clicking the Ascending and Descending radio buttons in the Order box.
\par \pard\plain \s6\sb120 \b\f5 F2 Field Help Picklist - Auto List
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
When a user of your application edits a field using Set validation on a data entry screen, pressing F2 or clicking the right mouse button displays a picklist of the set of valid entries for the field.  The picklist also shows the description you entered f
or each valid entry.  The user can select a value for the field from the picklist by double-clicking a value in the list or by highlighting a value and pressing enter.
\par If you check the Auto List check box on the field's Set validation dialog, the He
lp picklist will automatically appear if the field fails validation.  Users can then select a valid entry from the picklist.  If the Validation Option you select for the field does not include Null and if Null is not a valid entry, users can hit the tab o
r enter key when the cursor first enters the field to bring up the Help picklist right away.
\par \pard\plain \s4\sb216\sa14\keepn \b\f5 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} NotNull.46}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Not Null}}{\f103  }{
\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Not Null}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0190}}{\f103  }Not Null
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Not Null validation simply means that a field must have an entry.  When a user edits the field or adds a new record to the table, the field cannot be left empty.
\par Not Null validation is useful for fields that don't lend themselves to precise validation rules but that should have an entry.  For example, name fields in a customer or employee table don't normally comply with a set of rules that can be used for validat
ion.  However, name fields should not be left empty.  Not Null validation works well for such fields.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To set up Not Null validation for a field
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber40}1.\tab Select Not Null validation on the Type popup.  There's no information to enter on the Integrity dialog.
\par 2.\tab Click the Options popup to turn on validation for the field.  Choose the validation option that you want for the field.
\par 3.\tab C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber40}lick OK.
