\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Code}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0195}}{\f103  }Code
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 When you choose Code validation for a field, you write FoxPro code to validate the field.  At the time your code is run, the memory variable {\b\f11 slCurValue}
 contains the field value to validate.  Your code must set the logical memory variable {\b\f11 sllRetVal} to false (.F.) if the field fails validation.  Your code can return the error message to display if the 
field fails validation by assigning the message as a character string to the character memory variable {\b\f11 slcRetMess}.
\par Use Code validation if the validation rules you need to apply to a field are too complex for one of the standard ProMatrix validation types.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To create Code validation for a field
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber41}1.\tab Select Code validation on the Type popup.  ProMatrix transforms the Integrity dialog for Code validation.
\par 2.\tab E{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber41}nter your code in the text box on the Integrity dialog.  Use the following memory variables in your code:
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx2070\cellx7290 \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sa60\sl281\slmult1\intbl \f5\fs20 {\b Memory Variable}\cell {\b Purpose\cell }\pard\plain \intbl \f5\fs20 \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx2070\cellx7290 \pard\plain 
\s16\sb60\sl281\slmult1\intbl \f5\fs20 {\b\f11 slCurValue\cell }Contains the field value to validate.  Use this value in your code validation rules.\cell \pard\plain \intbl \f5\fs20 \row \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1\intbl \f5\fs20 {\b\f11 
sllRetVal\cell }\pard \s16\sb60\sl281\slmult1\intbl Returns the result of the validation.  If validation fails, set {\b\f11 SllRetval} to F.  If validation passes, set to T.\cell \pard\plain \intbl \f5\fs20 \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx2070
\cellx7290 \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1\intbl \f5\fs20 {\b\f11 slcRetMess\cell }\pard \s16\sb60\sa60\sl281\slmult1\intbl Returns an error message to display if validation fails.  Assign a character string to {\b\f11 slcRetMess}.  For example:

\par \pard \s16\sb120\sa60\sl281\slmult1\intbl {\b\f11\fs16 slcRetMess = "Field must have at least 4 characters"}\cell \pard\plain \intbl \f5\fs20 \row \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 3.\tab 
When you're finished entering your validation code, click the Options popup to turn on validation for the field.  Choose the validation option that you want for the field.
\par 4.\tab Click OK.
\par \pard\plain \s6\sb120 \b\f5 Find Program
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
You can call a program to handle a field's validation instead of entering validation code in the text box.  Put your call to the program in the text box.  You can click the Find Program button to find the name of the program.  When you find the name of th
e program, ProMatrix replaces any code you've entered in the text box with the name of the program followed by "()".
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb180\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Warning } If you've entered
 code in the text box to validate a field, don't access the Find Program button.  If you do, you could inadvertently replace your code with a program file name.
\par \pard\plain \s4\sb216\sa14\keepn \b\f5 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} SameAs.48}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Same As}}{\f103  }{
\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Same As}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0200}}{\f103  }Same As
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
Same As validation provides a shortcut that lets you validate a field the same as another field. If several fields use the same validation rules, you only need to set up the validation for one field.  You can use Same As validation for the other fields to
 validate them just like the field you set up.
\par Same As validation is particular
ly useful for Referential Integrity validation.  Often many ancillary tables in an application have foreign keys that match the primary key of a master table.  In this case, you only need to set up Referential Integrity validation for one of the ancillary
 tables.  You can then take the shortcut of using Same As validation for the other ancillary tables.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To set up Same As validation for a field
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber42}1.\tab Select Same As validation on the Type popup.
\par 2.\tab Identify the field whose validation this field should use.  Enter the name and extension of the table that contains the field and the name of the field on the Integrity dialog.
\par 3.\tab Click the Options popup to turn on validation for the field.  Choose the validation option that you want.
\par 4.\tab C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber42}lick OK.
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb340\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} ReferentialIntegrity.49}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $}
 Referential Integrity}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Referential Integrity}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0205}}{
\f103\fs24  }Referential Integrity
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sa180\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 C. J. Date ({\i An Introduction to Database Systems}, Volume I, Addison-Wesley Publishing Company, Reading, MA, 1987) defined the following referential integrity rule of the relational model:
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx2070\cellx6948 \pard \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1\intbl {\b\i Referential Integrity}\cell \pard \s16\sb120\sa60\sl281\slmult1\intbl If a table includes a foreign key (FK
) matching the primary key (PK) of some table T, every value of FK must be either:
\par a) Equal to the value of PK in some record in table T, or 
\par \pard \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1\intbl b) Entirely null.\cell \pard\plain \intbl \f5\fs20 \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx2070\cellx6948 \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1\intbl \f5\fs20 {\b\i Primary Key\cell }
The field or combination of fields that uniquely identifies each record in a table.\cell \pard\plain \intbl \f5\fs20 \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx2070\cellx6948 \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1\intbl \f5\fs20 {\b\i Foreign Key\cell }\pard 
\s16\sb120\sa180\sl281\slmult1\intbl A field or combination of fields in one table whose values are required to match those of the primary key of another table.\cell \pard\plain \intbl \f5\fs20 \row \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
The referential integrity rule is concerned with maintaining valid references between primary keys and related foreig
n keys.  If you use ProMatrix's Referential validation type to validate foreign keys, your ProMatrix applications will adhere to the referential integrity rule for the situations in which it might be violated.  The next section of this chapter titled {\i 
Referential Validation} explains how to set up Referential validation for a field.
\par The situations that can lead to a violation of the referential integrity rule are described below along with the action you can take to prevent the violation:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber43}\'b7\tab } {\b {\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber43}Inserts - Entry or Change of Foreign Key Fields}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
When foreign key fields are entered or changed on data entry screens, the foreign key fields (a) must match a primary key in the table to which the foreign key is related or (b) be left blank (if you permit blank foreign keys).
\par {\b Action:}
  If you use the Referential validation type to validate a foreign key, it won't be possible to enter a foreign key that doesn't match a primary key in the related table.   If you select the On validation option, the foreign key cannot be null.  
If you allow null foreign keys, select the On/Null option.  It is not usually desirable to allow a null foreign key.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber44}\'b7\tab }{\b U{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber44}pdates - Updating the Primary Key} 
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 If a user updates a primary key that another table uses as a foreign key, the foreign key loses its reference to a primary key and the referential integrity rule is violated.
\par {\b Action:}  When you set up Referential validation for a foreign key, select one of the following four rules on the Integrity dialog for handling updates.
\par \pard\plain \s64\fi-360\li720\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx720 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber45}\'b7\tab }{\b Restrict} - Allow the primary key update only if there are no records with matching foreign keys. 
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b Set Null} - Nullify the foreign key values on all matching records.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b Cascade} - Automatically update the matching foreign key values to the new value of the primary key.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b No Change} - Allow the primary key update without updating matching foreign keys.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\keepn\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b D{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber45}eletes - Deletion of Primary Key} 
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 If a user deletes a record containing a primary key that another table uses as a foreign key, the foreign key loses its reference to a primary key and the referential integrity rule is violated.

\par {\b Action:}  When you set up Referential validation for a foreign key, select one of the following four rules on the Integrity dialog for handling deletes.
\par \pard\plain \s64\fi-360\li720\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx720 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber46}\'b7\tab }{\b Restrict} - Allow the deletion only if there are no records with a foreign key matching the primary key about to be deleted.. 
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b Set Null} - Nullify the foreign key values on all matching records.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b Cascade} - Automatically delete all records in all tables with the matching foreign key.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b N{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber46}o Change} - Allow the deletion without regard to matching foreign keys.
