Filter Expression
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 You may enter a filter expression at the bottom of the Integrity dialog to restrict the primary keys available for Referential validation.  
\par For example, let's say a customer table used a
 store location code plus a customer number as the primary key and the invoice table used those same fields as a foreign key.  If you wanted to restrict invoice data entry to certain stores, you could enter a filter expression that restricted the store lo
cation codes available for validation to those stores.  Then, when users entered invoices, they could not enter invoices for any other stores.
\par You can also use the filter to select a code type in a Reference, or lookup, table that contains multiple code typ
es.  For example, some developers like to use one lookup table to hold multiple types of valid codes for many different data fields.  A record in such a lookup table normally contains a field for the valid code, a field for a descriptive label and an ID f
ield that identifies the code type.  When you set up Referential validation for a data field that stores a particular code type, you can set a filter on the lookup table's ID field to select the code type that should be used to validate the field.
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb120\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Important } Any quotes you enter into the filter expression must be single quotes, not double quotes.
\par \pard\plain \s4\sb216\sa14\keepn \b\f5 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} ReferentialValidationSetup.52}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $}
 Referential Validation Setup}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Referential Validation Setup}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0220}}{
\f103  }Referential Validation Setup
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb120\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Tip }
 The following steps require you to make entries into fields that have F2 picklist help.  This means that instead of typing your entry, you can press F2 or click your right mouse button to display a picklist of valid entries.  Select the entry you want on
 the picklist and double-click the entry or press Enter.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To set up Referential validation for a field
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber48}1.\tab Select Referential validation on the Integrity dialog's Type popup.  ProMatrix transforms the Integrity dialog for Referential validation.
\par 2.\tab C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber48}lick the Reference Table field.  Enter the name and extension of the primary key table.
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 3.\tab 
Tab to or click the top Foreign Key Field.  Enter the foreign key field name.  If the foreign key is compound, enter the names of the remaining foreign key fields in the remaining fields spaces.  The foreign key fields should be listed from top to bott
om in the order in which they make up the foreign key.
\par 4.\tab 
If you've previously identified the primary key of the reference table on the table Properties dialog, ProMatrix automatically enters the primary key fields on the Integrity dialog.  If not, enter the reference table's primary key in the Primary Key Fi
elds column.
\par 5.\tab If the Foreign Key and Primary Key fields have been entered properly, the corresponding field names in the keys will be side-by-side in the two Key Fields columns.  If not, adjust your entries until corresponding field names are o
n the same line in the columns.
\par 6.\tab In the Update Rule box click the radio button for the update rule you want applied.
\par 7.\tab In the Delete Rule box click the radio button for the delete rule you want applied.
\par 8.\tab If applicable, enter a filter expression in the Filter Expression box.
\par 9.\tab Click the Option popup to turn on validation for the field.  If the foreign key is compound, use a validation option that allows an override (see below).
\par 10.\tab Click OK.
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb120\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Tip}  You normally also set up the F2 Help picklist when you set up Referential validation for a field.  See the {\i F2 Field Help Picklist}
 section below to learn how.
