\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
As you are setting up referential integrity for an application's tables, you are defining the relations among the tables.  Some developers use the terms "parent" and "child" to refer to related tables.  A child table is actually a table with a foreign key
 that must match a primary key in a parent table.  If you set up referential integrity for all foreign keys, you define the parent-child relationships at the same time.  There's nothing left to do to set up table relations.
\par Y
ou can print or view an application's table relations by running the Related Tables report that ProMatrix puts into every application.  When you set up tables to create an application object, ProMatrix automatically sets the relations among related tables
.
