\par \pard\plain \s67\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
The F2 Help picklist shows the description expression you enter in the Desc field in the F2 box on the Referential validation Integrity dialog.  You create the description expression from fields in the Reference table.  The Desc push button in the F2 box 
displays the FoxPro Expression Builder to allow you to more easily create a description expression.  The expression must be character type.
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb120\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Example:}
  In an inventory system, a customer table normally contains a customer number as the primary key plus other fields including the customer name.  An invoice table contains the customer number as a foreign key.  When setting up Referential validation to va
lidate the customer number field in the invoice table using the customer table as the reference table, you should enter the customer name field i
n the F2 Desc field on the Integrity dialog.  If you do, when the customer number in the invoice table is edited and F2 pressed, the list of customer numbers that appears will also have the customer name to identify each customer number.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
The output from the expression you enter displays a description for each entry in the picklist.  The expression you enter should consist of fields from the Reference table, functions that convert non-character fields to character and spacing between field
s if there is more than one field in the expression.
\par You can click the Desc... button to use the FoxPro Expression Builder to create the expression.  The Expression Builder gives you easy access to the Reference table fields and FoxPro functions that you need to build the expression.
\par The expression you enter determines:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber50}\'b7\tab }T{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber50}he spacing between the fields.  Include spaces between fields with a space expression like this:
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 {\b +' '+
\par }The number of spaces between the single quotes determines the spacing between fields.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber51}\'b7\tab }The Type of the
 expression.  The expression must be character type.  That means you must convert non-character fields to the character type when you build the expression.  Use FoxPro data type conversion functions to convert non-character fields to the character type.

\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }T{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber51}he length of each field.  Use FoxPro character functions to fix the length of the fields in expression.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 For example, if the primary key in the Reference table were an employee number, you might want to use the employee last name and first name as the desc
ription expression.  Therefore, you might enter the description expression like this:
\par \pard\plain \s34 \b\f11\fs20 PADR(TRIM(LNAME) +', '+ TRIM(FNAME), 40)
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb180\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Note  }
The F2 Help Picklist window automatically sizes itself based on the width of the description expression and the Reference table primary key field.  The width of the description field used in sizing the picklist window is based on the length of the string 
returned by the description expression for the first record in the Reference table.  Therefore, you may want to fix the length of the string returned by the description expression as is done in the above example.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
If you use the Expression Builder to create the List Box Expression, click the Verify button to check the validity of the expression you build.  If the expression is not character type, it will be found to be invalid.
