\par \pard\plain \s4\sb216\sa14\keepn \b\f5 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} UsingCleanupCodeValidationwithOverrideOption.63}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {
\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Using Cleanup Code Validation with Override Option}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Using Cleanup Code Validation with Override Option}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote 
\pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0275}}{\f103  }Using Cleanup Code Validation with Override Option
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
If you use Cleanup Code to apply additional validation rules to a field and if you use a Validation Option that lets users override validation, you must enter your Cleanup Code as shown below.  This illustration of Cleanup Code as
sumes that your Cleanup Code includes code to both apply an additional field validation rule and to update or calculate other fields using the new field value entered.
\par The memory variable sllOverride is set to .T.  in the ProMatrix validation routine if either the Integrity validation rules or your additional validation rules fail but an override value is entered.
\par \pard\plain \s78 \b\f11\fs18 IF sllOverride\tab && Validation failed and override entered.
\par    * Insert code to update or calculate other fields using  
\par    * new field value.
\par ELSE\tab \tab \tab && Validation passed.
\par    * Insert code to apply additional validation rules.
\par      IF <additional validation condition fails>
\par         slcRetMess = 'error message'
\par         sllRetVal = .F.  && Will cause override prompt
\par                          && to display
\par      ELSE
\par         * Additional validation condition passed.
\par         * Again insert code to update or calculate other 
\par         * fields using new field value. 
\par      ENDIF 
\par ENDIF
\par \pard\plain \s4\sb216\sa14\keepn \b\f5 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} CodeValidationandCleanupCodeStorage.64}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {
\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Code Validation and Cleanup Code Storage}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Code Validation and Cleanup Code Storage}}{\f103  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 
\b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0280}}{\f103  }Code Validation and Cleanup Code Storage
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 ProMatrix stores the code 
you enter on the Code Validation and Cleanup Code dialogs as functions in a program named S<Prefix>VC.PRG.  ProMatrix stores the Code Validation and Cleanup Code functions for all fields in an application in this one program.  The names of a field's Code 
Validation and Cleanup Code functions are stored in the CODE_FUNC and CLEAN_FUNC fields in the field's record in the fields data dictionary table (S<Prefix>DD2.DBF).  Whenever you enter new code or change the code for a field, ProMatrix recreates the S<Pr
efix>VC.PRG program when you exit the Integrity dialog.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb362\sa43\keepn \b\f5\fs36 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} MemoryVariableswithFieldProperties.65}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {
\cs82\fs16\up6 $} Memory Variables with Field Properties}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Memory Variables with Field Properties}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION1:0285}}{\f103\fs24  }Memory Variables with Field Properties
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
You can include a memory variable in your application's data dictionary and set up field properties for it.  You can set up Integrity validation, a label, field security, a screen message, field-level help text, an error message and a WHEN expression.

\par Then, if you put the memory variable on a screen as an input field (GET), ProMatrix will treat it just like a table field.  When application users edit the field, it'll have whatever field properties you've defined for it {\f1 \'be}
 field-level help, validation, messages and so on.
\par When ProMatrix creates a new project, it creates a table named S<Prefix>DMVU and adds it to the application's data dictionary.  This is the user (developer) memory variable table.  Initially, the table contains one character field named Filler.  You inclu
de a memory variable in the data dictionary by adding a field with the memory variable name to the memory variable table.  When you include a
 memory variable with the same name as an input field on a screen, ProMatrix automatically inserts the field-level clauses that implement the data dictionary field properties.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To add a memory variable to the data dictionary
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber59}1.\tab Open the Data Builder from the ProMatrix Tools menu or the Data Manager from your application's Admin menu.
\par 2.\tab Highlight the table named S<Prefix>DMVU in the Tables list.
\par 3.\tab Click the Structure button.  ProMatrix displays the Table Structure dialog.
\par 4.\tab Using the Table Structure dialog, add a field to S<Prefix>DMVU that has the memory variable name.  Enter the type and width appropriate for the memory variable.  Click OK.  Click Yes to make structure changes permanent.
\par 5.\tab Highlight the memory variable name in the Fields list.
\par 6.\tab S{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber59}
et up the field properties you want the memory variable to have.  You may set up the Integrity, Label, Permissions, Message, Comments, Help, Error and When properties.  The Audit Trail, Unique, Default and Picture field properties cannot be used with 
memory variables.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To include the memory variable on a screen as an input field
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 The steps described below assume the screen already exists.  The description does not include all the steps you need to take to create a screen with controls.
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber60}1.\tab 
On the ProMatrix Object Builder, select the menu option for the screen that will contain the memory variable field.  ProMatrix  displays the screen set Object Editor.  
\par 2.\tab C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber60}lick the Table Setup button on the Object Editor.  ProMatrix displays the Table Setup dialog.  If there are no tables shown in the Tables list, add the S<Prefix>DMVU table to the Tables list.  Click OK.
\par \pard\plain \s75\li360\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Note}
  The Table Setup dialog's Tables list must contain a table before ProMatrix will automatically insert field properties code in screens.  The S<Prefix> DMVU table is added to the Tables list temporarily to trigger the code insertion.
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 3.\tab Highlight the screen in the Screen Objects list.  Click the Edit button.  ProMatrix displays the FoxPro Screen Builder for the screen.  Add the memory variable field to the scre
en as an input field.  Include "m." (without the quotes) as a prefix to the memory variable name wherever it's used in the Screen Builder.
\par 4.\tab Close the FoxPro Screen Builder and save your changes.
\par 5.\tab As ProMatrix returns to the screen set Object Editor, it inserts the code that activates the field properties for the memory variable.
\par 6.If you added the S<Prefix>DMVU table to the Table Setup dialog's Tables list in step 2, click the Table Setup button and remove the table from the Tables list {\f1 \'be}  it's served its purpose.  Click OK to exit the Table Setup dialog.
\par 7.\tab Click OK to exit the screen set Object Editor.
