\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 An application can run a report directly from a menu option or as a called object.  
\par \pard\plain \s47\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\cs71\b Tip}{\cs71   }
You might want to set up a report to run from a menu option if the report is part of a series of menu options that perform a process.  For example, in a payroll system you might place a menu option to print a payroll control report right after the option 
that runs payroll calculations.  The menu option for the payroll control report would be a reminder that the report should be printed and reviewed before printing payroll checks.  You would also set u
p a report to run from a menu option if you wanted to use ProMatrix's menu security feature to restrict user access to the report.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
You can create a report as a Menu Object or a Called Object.  In either case, you select Report or Label as the new object type on the New Object dialog and enter a file name for the report.  After you enter the report's name, ProMatrix displays the repor
t Object Editor.
\par The report Object Editor serves the same purpose as the Report Manager's Report Editor.  The two editors cont
ain push buttons that are functionally equivalent.  You use the report Object Editor to create a report just like you would use the Report Editor.  The Report Editor's Run button is called the Try It button on the report Object Editor.  The User Functions
 list box is replaced with the Called Objects list box, but they both serve the same purpose.
