\par \pard\plain \s66\sa120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
You access the User Data screen from the Users option on the PM-Admin menu's ProMatrix Security popup.  The User Data screen is where you enter and maintain information about the people who will be using ProMatrix.  
\par \pard\plain \s67\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 ProMatrix encrypts the data you enter on the User Data screen before storing it in the User table S<Prefix>SUSR.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Click the Add button and enter a new user's information in the fields shown.  The fields on the User Data screen are described below.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\keepn\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber72}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b User Number}
\par \pard \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \tab A 10 character field used to identify the user.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\cs71\b User ID}
\par \tab A 10 character field which identifies the user to ProMatrix.  The entry must be unique through the first four characters because those characters are used to create unique .APP file names for the applications you build.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\cs71\b F3 Edit}
\par \tab Enter a "Y" if the user should have the right to edit field F3 help text and F2 Help picklists while editing data on an input screen.  Enter an "N" if the user should not have this right.  If System Access Security is off, defaults to "Y".
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\cs71\b S{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber72}tatus}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
A 10 character field that can be used to store any information you like about the user.  When a user enters ProMatrix, the contents of this field are stored in the global memory variable sgcStatus so that you can make use of it without having to extract i
t from the encrypted User record.
\par An example of how this field might be used in your application:  You might want to add a menu pad and popup to the main menu for those users who have been identified as Administrators.  The added popup might only have opt
ions pertaining to the administration of the system.  You could then make a rule that says that an "A" in the first character of the Status field identifies the user as an administrator.  In the application's main program, you could add the administration
 popup to the main menu if the first character of the sgcStatus memory variable is an "A". 
\par \pard\plain \s79\li360 \b\f11\fs20 IF LEFT(sgcStatus,1) = 'A'
\par DO Admin.mpr
\par \pard \s79\li360\sa120 ENDIF
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber73}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b L{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber73}og-On Status}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Contains a "Y" if the user is currently logged-on.  Contains an "N" if the user is currently logged-off
.  If a user is logged-on when the application is abnormally terminated  due to a power failure, rebooting, etc., the contents of this field may be incorrect.  If the user has not been given Multiple Log-On rights as described below, the user will not be 
allowed to re-enter the application.  In this case, another user will have to change the contents of this field to an "N" so the user can re-enter the application.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber74}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b M{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber74}ultiple Log-On}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A "Y" means the user can log-on to the application from more than one compu
ter at the same time.  This user can also re-enter the application if it terminates abnormally as described above.  An "N" means that the user can only log-on if the contents of the Log-On Status field is "N".  At least one user should be given this right
 so that all users would not be locked out of the application if there is a power failure, etc.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber75}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b F{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber75}irst Name}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A 20 character field containing the user's first name.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber76}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b M{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber76}iddle Name}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A 20 character field containing the user's middle name.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber77}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b L{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber77}ast Name}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A 20 character field containing the user's last name.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber78}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b T{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber78}emporary Password}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
When a user is first added on this screen, enter a temporary password in this field.  Then, when the user enters the application for the first time they will be prompted to enter a new password of their own choosing.  Any time you make an entry in this fi
eld, the next entry by the user will require them to enter a new password.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber79}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b P{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber79}assword Last Change}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 This field contains the date of the last password change.  Blanking-out this field will cause the user to be required to enter a new password upon the next entry into the application.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber80}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b P{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber80}assword Period}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
This field contains a 3-digit number that represents the number of days that, when added to the Password Last Change date, is the date on which the user must next change passwords.  An entry of zero means that the user can keep the same password indefinit
ely.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber81}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber81}ontrol Permission Group}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A 3 character field used to assign the user the same control permissions as all other members of the same group.  This
 way, individual control permissions do not have to be assigned to each member of the group.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber82}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber82}ontrol Permissions}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
The Control Permissions push button brings up the Control Permissions dialog where control permissions are assigned.  If there is an entry in the Control Permission Group field, the Control Permissions dialog will only display the permissions assigned to 
the group.  You may not change these assignments.  The group's control permissions may be changed through the Control Permission Groups screen
 accessed from the PM-Admin menu's Security popup.  If there isn't an entry in the Control Permission Group field, you can make the control permission assignments for this user.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber83}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b F{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber83}ield Permission Group}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A 3 character field used to assign the user the same field permissions as all other members of the same group.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber84}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b M{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber84}enu Permission Group}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A 3 character field used to assign the user the same menu permissions as all other members of the same group.  This way, individual menu permissions do not have to be assigne
d to each member of the group.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber85}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b M{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber85}enu Permissions}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
The Menu Permissions push button brings up the Menu Permissions dialog where menu permissions are assigned.  If there is an entry in the Menu Permission Group field, the Menu Permissions dialog will only display the permissions assigned to the group.  You
 may not change these assignments.  The group's menu permissions may be changed through the Menu Permission Groups screen.  If there isn't an entry in the Menu Permission Group field, you can make the menu permission assignments for this user.
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb340\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} UserPassword.88}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $}
 User Password}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} User Password}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION3:0020}}{\f103\fs24  }
User Password
\par \pard\plain \s66\sa120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
You access the User Password screen from the Passwords option on the PM-Admin menu's ProMatrix Security popup.  The User Password screen is where you view and change user passwords as well as identify which users can access the screen.  
\par \pard\plain \s67\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 ProMatrix encrypts the data you enter on the User Password screen before storing it in the User table S<Prefix>SUSR.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 You can't add user records on the User Password screen.  You add user records on the User Data screen.  Passwords are maintained on a separate User Password screen for additional security.  
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb180\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Tip}
  If system access security is critical in an application you create with ProMatrix, users of the application can use the Access field (see below) on the User Password screen to restrict access to passwords to those with the highest security clearance. 

\par \pard \s47\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 If your application needs even more password security than that, you can remove the User Password screen and the Passwords Report from the application entirely.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 The fields on the User Password screen are described below.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber86}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b P{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber86}assword}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A 10 character field that contains the user's current password.  Any time you make an entry in this field, the next system access by the user will require them to enter this password.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber87}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b L{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber87}ast Change}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 This field contains the date of the last password change.  Blanking-out this field will require the user to enter a new password upon the next entry into the application.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber88}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b A{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber88}ccess}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Use of this field provides an additional level of password privacy beyond that which is provided by Menu Security.  Additional privacy is required because:
\par \pard\plain \s64\fi-360\li720\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx720 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber89}\'b7\tab }A user that assigns menu permissions to users may not be authorized to access this screen.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }A{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber89} user that does not have the authority to access this screen might have the authority to access the Admin Tools screen where he could simply turn off Menu Security.
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A "Y" in this field means that the user has the right to access this screen (assuming the user has been given the Menu Security permission).  Once one or more
 users have had a "Y" entered in this field, only those users with a "Y"  can access this screen.  As long as all users have an "N" in this field, any user that has been given the Menu Security permission to access this screen can have access.
\par \pard\plain \s75\li360\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Tip}
  If you expect that users of your application will use the Access field to provide additional password security, you should remove the Passwords Report from the application's Security popup.   If you want to provide similar security while running ProMatr
ix, you can delete the Passwords Report files.
