 Password Setup}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Password Setup}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION3:0025}}{\f103\fs24  }
Password Setup
\par \pard\plain \s66\sa120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 The Password Setup screen on the ProMatrix Security popup is where you define the rules for entering new passwords on the New Password dialog.  
\par \pard\plain \s67\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 The fields on the Password Setup dialog are described below.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber90}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b W{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber90}arning Days}
\par \pard \s62\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 
A numeric field which represents the number of days prior to the password expiration date that a warning dialog will be displayed.  The dialog will show the expiration date and allow the user to change passwords immediately.
\par \pard \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber91}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b C{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber91}hange Character}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
A one character field that holds the character that that when appended to the password entered on the User Log-On dialog, signifies that the user wants to enter a new password.  The default character is a question mark, "?".
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber92}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b N{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber92}o ID in Password}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Checking this box will prevent users from using their ID in their password.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber93}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b M{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber93}inimum Length}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A number from 1 to 10 which represents the least number of characters that can make up a password.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber94}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b M{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber94}aximum Length}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 A number from 1 to 10 which represents the greatest number of characters that can make up a password.
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\keepn\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber95}\'b7\tab }{\cs71\b P{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber95}rior Passwords}
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
A number that represents how many prior passwords will be checked to prevent duplicate entry.  An entry of one means that the user's current password cannot be reused.  An entry of two means that the user's current and immediately preceding passwords cann
ot be reused.
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb340\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} SecurityReports.90}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $}
 Security Reports}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Security Reports}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION3:0030}}{\f103\fs24  }
 Security Reports
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 There are two reports on the ProMatrix Security popup.  They are the Users and Passwords reports.  They are run from menu options rather tha
n from the Report Manager so that you can use Menu Security to prevent unauthorized users from running them.
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb180\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Tip}
  In the applications you build for distribution, you may want to "include" these reports in the .APP or .EXE file and not distribute the actual report files (.FRX, .FRT).  If you distribute the report files, any user that can access the Report Manager co
uld add the reports to the Report Manager and run them.  They could also possibly be run from FoxPro.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb362\sa43\keepn \b\f5\fs36 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} MenuSecurity.91}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $}
 Menu Security}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} Menu Security}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION3:0035}}{\f103\fs24  }
Menu Security
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Menu Security prevents users from accessing menu options that the system supervisor decides they should not access.  
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb180\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Note}
  This section describes Menu Security in terms of how you set it up for ProMatrix.  However, the descriptions of how Menu Security works and how you set it up apply equally to the applications you build with ProMatrix.  
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 ProMatrix uses GENMENUX to remove those menu options that a user has not been authorized to access.  Using this method, users do not even see the options that they cannot access.   
\par Because Menu Security is assigned to individual users, Menu Security is disabled if System Access Security is turned off.
\par When ProMatrix is installed, Menu Security is turned off.  This is done because users and their passwords must be set up and menu permissions must be assigned before Menu Security is turned on through the Admin Tools screen.  
\par \pard\plain \s47\sb180\sa180\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Tip}  Distribute your applications with Menu Security turned off.
