\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Regardless of how extensively a developer tests software, errors occur. Consequently, applications need an error-handler that deals with errors gracefully and records useful information about the errors.

\par The ProMatrix error-handler traps errors that occur in ProMatrix and applications.  The error-handler determines the severity of the error and handles it accordingly.  Information about an error is recorded in an errors table.
\par \pard\plain \s66\sa120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
You can reach the Errors screen from the PM-Admin menu or from the Admin menu of an application.  The Errors screen on the PM-Admin menu shows information about errors that occur while you're running ProMatrix.  The Errors screen on an application's Admin
 menu lets you view information about the errors that occur while users are running the application.
\par \pard\plain \s67\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 You use the information on the Errors dialog to resolve errors and debug your application.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 When the Errors dialog first appears, it shows information for the last error that occurred for the current user.  The errors are shown in descending order of the time and date the errors occurred.  
\par \pard \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1\keepn You can:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber132}\'b7\tab }{\b Order:}  Change the order to ascending through the Order button on the Errors dialog.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b All Users:}  If you've implemented System Access Security in your application, you can view errors for all users who have run the application by clicking the All Users radio button in the Filter box.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b All Apps:}  If the application is sharing its error file with another application, you can view errors for all applications by clicking the All Apps radio button in the Filter box.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b Screen Controls:}  You cannot edit or add error records but you can delete them.  You should delete the error records before you package your application. 
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b Memory:}  Click the Memory button to see the contents of memory variables and arrays when the error occurred.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }{\b S{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber132}tatus:}  Click the Status button to see the status of the FoxPro environment when the error occurred.
