og allows a user to quickly find records using either the active table's current index key or primary key.  The fields in the current index key are displayed in the top half of the Find dialog.  The field(s) in the primary key are displayed in the bottom 
half.  The user can enter values into either key fields to Find a record.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 When the user changes the order of the records displayed on the screen through the Order screen control, the current index key fields are automatically changed the next time the Find dialog is displayed.

\par If more than one record meets the search criteria entered, ProMatrix displays all the records that meet the search criteria in a Browse.  The user can then highlight the desired record and close the Browse to display the record on the screen.
\par \pard\plain \s6\sb120 \b\f5 Case Sensitivity
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
The Find dialog contains a Match Case check box that will cause the Find to perform a case-sensitive search for character fields.  The case-sensitive search is much faster because it doesn't use the UPPER function that's required when case is ignored. 

\par The fields on the Find dialog use the picture clauses stored in the data dictionary.  If a picture clause contains an "!" to force upper case entry, the Match Case check box is automatically checked and the fast case-sensitive search will be performed.  

\par {\b Important Tip}  If you force a character field to upper case entry by using a picture clause with an "!", the fast case-sensitive Find will always be performed for the field.  Entries into the table field on a data screen will be forced
 to upper case.  When a user performs a Find on the field:
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 1.\tab The Match Case check box will be automatically checked on the Find dialog, and 
\par 2.\tab The user's entry into the field on the Find dialog will be forced to upper case, which will match the case of entries in the table field.  
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
This approach automatically results in the fast case-sensitive search without requiring the user to worry about the case of the entry on the Find dialog.  However, it must be acceptable for the character field to contain all upper case letters. 
