}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} The Problem}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION6:0000}}{\f103\fs24  }The Problem
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 Drive letters are used to identify the physical or logical drive where files are stored.
  ProMatrix keeps track of the location of a project's files by storing the paths to the files in certain system tables.  The stored paths include drive letters.  Also, as you build an application, you may include drive letters in the paths to the tables 
you enter into the application's data dictionary.  
\par In some situations, storing drive letters presents problems because drive letters are relative to the computer accessing the drives.  For example, let's say you install ProMatrix on a network drive known t
o your computer as drive G.  Then, you create a project on the network drive.  ProMatrix will store "G" as the drive letter in the path to the project's files.  Let's also say that to your co-developer's computer, the network drive is drive H.  Now, if th
e co-developer runs ProMatrix from the network drive and tries to open your project, ProMatrix will try to find the project's files on drive G.  Of course, ProMatrix won't be able to find the project's files because to your co-developer's computer your dr
ive G is drive H.
\par Similarly, if you develop an application that stores drive letters in the data dictionary paths to application tables, the drive letters might be incorrect for the computer that runs your end-application.
\par So, you can see that although storing drive letters is necessary to locate files, problems occur when the stored drive letters are used by different computers.
\par Fortunately, ProMatrix provides a solution to these problems.  The solution is ProMatrix's unique drive letter swapping.
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb120\keepn \b\f5\fs28 {\f103 \page }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 #} TheSolution.129}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 $}
 The Solution}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 K} The Solution}}{\f103\fs24  }{\cs82\f103\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s83 \b\f5\fs20 {\cs82\fs16\up6 +} SECTION6:0005}}{\f103\fs24  }T
he Solution
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 While you're running ProMatrix or while users are running an application you create with ProMatrix, ProMatrix can provide drive letter swapping.  Drive letter swapping lets you tell ProMatrix to:
\par \pard\plain \s62\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\f1 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber136}\'b7\tab }Store an arbitrary drive letter in the path to a file instead of the drive letter your computer uses to locate the file.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }S{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber136}wap the drive letter stored in the path to a file with the drive letter your computer uses to locate the file.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 {\b An example of the use of drive letter swapping:}  If an application 
you are creating is using tables on your drive G, but you know that the end-user of your application will have the tables on drive C,  you can tell ProMatrix to store "C" as the drive letter to the tables in the data dictionary.  Then, when the end-user r
uns the application, the application will find the tables correctly on the end-user's drive C without the need for drive letter swapping.  However, when you use the application's data dictionary during development, you can tell ProMatrix to swap the store
d C for an H so that your computer can find the tables.
\par \pard\plain \s47\sa120\sl281\slmult1\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \f5\fs20 {\b Note}
  You could handle this example differently.  You could let ProMatrix store drive letter G in the paths to the tables.  Then, the end-user could use ProMatrix's drive letter swapping to substitute drive letter C for G whenever paths are needed.  However, 
it's probably better to avoid drive letter swapping by end-users.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sb120\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 {\b Another example of the use of drive letter swapping:  }If a co-developer needs to open a project you have created on your network driv
e G, but the co-developer's computer sees the drive as H, the co-developer can tell ProMatrix to swap an H for every drive letter G it encounters.
\par \pard\plain \s65\sb120 \b\f5\fs20 To set up drive letter swapping for a computer
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 {\*\bkmkstart D2HBulletNumber137}1.\tab S{\*\bkmkend D2HBulletNumber137}
et a DRVSWAP environment variable to the path and file name of a .DBF file that will contain the drive letter swapping instructions.  If you want drive letter swapping for the computer whenever you run ProMatrix, include the following line in the comp
uter's AUTOEXEC.BAT file.  Otherwise, enter the line at the DOS prompt before running ProMatrix:
\par \pard\plain \s79\li360\sa120 \b\f11\fs20 SET DRVSWAP=<path>\\<file name.DBF>
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 
The path should be to a directory on the computer's local drive.  The file name can be anything you want.  The file extension must be .DBF.  You do not create this file.  ProMatrix will create it for you when you select the Drive Letter option on the PM-A
dmin menu after executing this line.
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 2.\tab Run ProMatrix.  ProMatrix displays this message:
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 "The Drive Letters table specified by the DRVSWAP environment variable does not exist.  To create it, go to the Drive Letters menu option."
\par Click OK.
\par \pard\plain \s76\fi-360\li360\sb120\sl281\slmult1\tx360 \f5\fs20 3.\tab Select the Drive Letters option on the PM-Admin menu.  ProMatrix displays the Drive Letters Browse.  Click the Add icon on the Browse toolbar or select Add on the Panel menu.
\par 4.\tab In the Stored field, enter the drive letter that ProMatrix will store in the paths to files.  In the Substitute field, enter the drive letter that you want ProMatrix to substitute for the stored drive letter whenever ProMatrix locates files.
\par \pard\plain \s70\li360\sb120\sa100\sl281\slmult1 \f5\fs20 For example, if a ProMatrix project's 
files will be located on the computer's H drive, but you want ProMatrix to store drive letter C, instead of H, in the paths to files on the H drive, you would enter C in the Stored field and H in the Substitute field.
